2011 100 Miles Of Nowhere (@Marymoor)
description:
This is a Seattle/Redmond version of www.fatcyclist.com\'s 100 Miles Of Nowhere ride. Our particular version of \"Nowhere\" is the Marymoor Velodrome in Redmond, Washington.
This is non-competitive, but we hope to get people out there cheering for us and heckling us (or both!)
registration: Fill out insurance form at the velodrome on the day of the ride.
notes: The scheduled date is Sunday, May 29, 8am-3pm. If it rains out we have rain dates of Memorial Day Monday, May 30, then possibly the evening of June 1 or the morning of June 5. Other days (between 5/29 and 6/5) are possible rain dates as well.

title: Keller Rohrback Road Race
description: The Keller Rohrback Road Race is the first event in the Northwest Summer Cup of races including Glenwood Circuit Race, Boston Harbor and Ronde Ohop that evoke the Belgian tradition of short, fast summer races.  Running through the town of Eatonville the race includes a mix of city and country roads.  All categories will have team wheels in/team wheels out. Select categories will have Neutral FSA Wheel Support.  The organizer is not responsible for wheels or equipment left at the race.
course: Race starts at XXXX.  11 mile rolling circuit perfect for late summer racing.  Course map and profile can be found at http://www.mapmyride.com/workout/41140116/
registration: Register online at USACycling or day of at Pioneer Farm.   Registration closes 20 minutes before the start of each event.  The entry fee includes $3 per rider per day for USA Cycling insurance. A current year USA Cycling Rider Waiver and Release form must be signed by the participant and, if under 18, by the parent or legal guardian.
notes: WSBA numbers will be used. The officials request that both bib numbers be clearly visible placed parallel with your jerseys side seam on the back and above the pockets. Frame number should be attached per WSBA instructions. Examples of proper placement: http://gcracingllc.com/numberplacement.aspx. Rental numbers are available for a $10 fee ($5 refundable). For out-of-state riders a $5 number refundable deposit will be assessed.
directions: Race registration and start are at Pioneer Farm, located approx. 1 hour and 50 minutes south of Seattle.  Address is 7716 Ohop Valley Road E., Eatonville, WA 98328

title: Grand Fondo Paradise
description: A 50 mile Grand Fondo from Ohop Valley to Paradise (Mt. Rainier).   Rules of the road in effect from start to finish and riders must navigate the park entrance legally or they will disqualified.  All riders must wait at the park entrance until Vehicle One clears the entrance.  Vehicle One will follow what it judges to be the main group of riders to the entrance.  Once Vehicle One gives the go ahead riders may begin the 17 mile ascent.  Vehicle One will then ascend to the finish and riders will be unsupported until then.  Finish time is taken off the first paint line of the cross walk at old Paradise Visitor Center.
course: Mashell-Nisqually Park field in the Ohop Valley to the cross walk at the Old Patadise Visitor Center parking lot. 50 miles total, 23 gradual ascent with lots of flats.  At the Park entrance the climbing grades progressively steeper for 17 miles.
registration: Riders must pre-register to participate.  No day of registration.  Riders must hold a valid USA Cycling Licence to register.  Note that you must also be logged into USACycling to register.
notes: Please note that while you can ride as hard as you want, in order to ensure the legal navigation of the park entrance and to prevent riders from benefiting from delays at the entrance riders may not begin final ascent until Vehicle One clears the entrance and gives the go ahead.  Rules of the road apply; groups must allow cars to pass.
directions: Parking will be at the Nisqually- Mashel State Park on the right under the power lines. From North or South on I-5 Take exit 127. Drive east on Hwy 512 for two miles, then take the Pacific Ave./Mt. Rainier exit south. Follow Pacific Ave. about five miles to where the road splits in a \"Y.\" Follow signs for Mt. Rainier (the left branch of the fork) taking Hwy 7 south. Drive about 17 miles, passing Ohop Valley Rd. At the top of the long sweeping hill turn right onto the Mashel Prairie Road on the right side. Go about  of a mile and park on the right side under the power lines.

All Gravity #4 - Mt Spokane
description: This will be the second mountain bike race to take place on Mt Spokane in a decade, lets make it a big one! There will be one day of racing this weekend with practice on Friday, Saturday, and Sunday morning!
course: Course is high speed singletrack, with some tight technical tree sections and loose dirt in the corners.
notes:
Registration:
Friday 1-4
Saturday 9-12
Sunday 9-11

Practice:
Friday 1-6
Saturday 10-5
Sunday 9-11

Race will start at 12pm Sunday, and is USA Cycling sanctioned. Awards will follow 45 minutes after the last pro racer.

Tons of sweet giveaways from Shimano, Deity Components, and Transition Bike Co!

Cost of race is $55 and gets you 3 days of shuttling!
WA State Park Discover Pass will be required for parking, its only $30/year (or $10/day) and lets you park at any state park I suggest buying one as our parks no longer get any tax dollars for funding.
Day licenses will be $5/day (one license for each day of riding, including Friday practice)
Register online by August 19, 2011  you can register online without making payment (select cash/check/card at race)

All riders will be required to have a license for practice AND race, whether it is a single day license purchased or a year license.
All racers will also be required to ride in a full faced helmet.
directions:
Park address:
N. 26107 Mt. Spokane Park Dr.
Mead, WA 99021

LODGING/CAMPING
There is lots of camping and lodging at the Bear Creek Lodge, and in the state park. Visit Bear Creek Lodge and Mt Spokane State Park for more info. Please do not call the rangers or Bear Creek Lodge with questions about the race, they will not know the answers.

title: The Schmuck
description: The 2011 version of The Schmuck Cyclocross Race is officially scheduled as the third event in the prestigious Inland Northwest Cyclocross Series.
course: The course is a mix of grass, dirt, sand, packed gravel, farmlands, and a variety of obstacles that will truly challenge all skill levels.
registration:
There is NO online registration for Inland Northwest Cyclocross Series events. Day of race registration only. for more details on registration and fees, please visit the event website.

http://www.emdesports.com/Race_Flyers/Inland_Northwest_Cyclocross_Series/inwcxs.html
notes:
Please visit the event website for series updates and follow The Schmuck specifically on our Facebook page.

Series Website:
http://www.emdesports.com/Race_Flyers/Inland_Northwest_Cyclocross_Series/inwcxs.html

Facebook Page:
http://www.facebook.com/pages/The-Schmuck-Cyclocross-Race/141056975926314?ref=ts
directions: Once in Colfax, proceed to north side of city (coming from the west, exit highway 26 east onto north highway 195). From highway 195, turn onto Cedar Street/Parkview Drive and fade immediately right onto Parkview Drive. Continue over the bridge, past the pool, and through Morton Street intersection. With the park on your left and high school track on your right, continue straight before curving left. Continue beyond the overflow parking area (located on your left) toward the back of the park complex to find registration, staging area, shelter, restrooms, and primary parking. Please do not park along the city access roadway between the primary and overflow parking areas.
